"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166650","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>Public Health England monitors trends in the level of childhood vaccination rates.</p><p>Although vaccination rates remain high, England has seen a small decline in coverage since 2013. The most recent figures, published in September 2019, show vaccine coverage increased slightly or remained the same compared to the last quarter for all vaccines, with the exception of flu vaccine uptake, when measured in children aged one, two and five years old. This data can be viewed at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/cover-of-vaccination-evaluated-rapidly-cover-programme-2019-to-2020-quarterly-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/cover-of-vaccination-evaluated-rapidly-cover-programme-2019-to-2020-quarterly-data</a></p><p>Yearly flu childhood vaccination rates can be viewed at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/839350/Surveillance_of_influenza_and_other_respiratory_viruses_in_the_UK_2018_to_2019-FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/839350/Surveillance_of_influenza_and_other_respiratory_viruses_in_the_UK_2018_to_2019-FINAL.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-31T17:28:31.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166650/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166650/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-28","Vaccination: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of childhood vaccination rates in England.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","6296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166651","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Strangford (Jim Shannon MP) on 29 October 2019 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2019-10-21/2735" target="_blank">2735</a>.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-31T17:35:44.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166651/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166651/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-28","Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effect of access to health services on trends in the level of vaccination rates in England.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","6297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166652","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-11-04","<p>​The UK has consistently advocated for sustained humanitarian access in all areas of Syria, including the north east, and is actively speaking to partners including Turkey and Iraq on this subject. We are committed to the renewal of Resolution 2249, which allows much needed humanitarian aid to be delivered cross-border into Syria, and will soon begin discussions with likeminded countries in the UN Security Council on this subject.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-11-04T16:03:40.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166652/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166652/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-28","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2019 to Question 1878, what recent steps his Department has taken to ensure that cross-border points remain (a) open and (b) accessible to humanitarian aid (i) workers and (ii) supplies.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","6429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166653","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>​For financial year 19/20, a programme fund of £201,401 has been allocated for implementing the Bishop of Truro’s recommendations. Separately, the office of the Prime Minister’s Special Envoy on Freedom of Religion or Belief has been allocated £73,453 this financial year to cover admin and travel costs. Funding for future years, both for the implementation of the recommendations and for the Special Envoy’s office, will be decided at a later stage. We have accepted and are working to deliver all the recommendations contained in the Bishop of Truro’s report. We do not intend to publish a strategic plan for delivering the recommendations, given the sensitivities around some of them.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-10-31T16:26:06.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166653/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166653/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-28","Persecution of Christians across the Globe Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what funding has been allocated to the implementation of the recommendations of the Bishop of Truro’s Review into the Persecution of Christians Worldwide in each of the next five years; and if he will publish his strategic plan for delivering those recommendations.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","6339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166654","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-01","<p>It is not possible to answer this question. This answer could only be provided by accessing a substantial number of referrals to ascertain how many relate to advances claimed after 18<sup>th</sup> September 2019. As a result, we estimate providing this information would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2019-11-01T10:59:45.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166654/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166654/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of universal credit claimants who have been referred for fraud relating to advance claims made after 18 September 2019.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","6512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166655","Department for International Development","false","2019-10-31","<p>As at 28 October, the breakdown of DFID staff deployed to other government departments to work on EU exit related tasks is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Office</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No. deployed</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DFID London</p></td><td><p>127</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DFID Scotland</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DFID Overseas</p></td><td><p>Less than 5</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson",,"2019-10-31T16:25:00.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166655/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166655/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-10-28","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many of his civil servants have been deployed to other Departments from his Department's (a) London office b) Scotland office and (c) offices overseas to work on tasks relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","6481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166656","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Department makes use of a range of channels to increase understanding of Universal Credit through social media and wider advertising. This includes signposting to sources of information which are written in an ‘easy-to-read’ format to help people make decisions on whether Universal Credit is appropriate for their circumstances.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We publish information in two key locations to help improve awareness of, and how to claim Universal Credit, which can be found at the following websites:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.understandinguniversalcredit.gov.uk/making-a-claim/before-you-claim/" target="_blank">https://www.understandinguniversalcredit.gov.uk/making-a-claim/before-you-claim/</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-detailed-information-for-claimants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-detailed-information-for-claimants</a></p><p> </p><p>If a person wishes to claim Universal Credit but requires assistance, they are clearly directed to either the Help to Claim service, or to the Universal Credit telephone helpline. Both can be useful to anyone who cannot use digital services.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support from helping people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time. This service is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly engage with a range of stakeholders, including welfare rights organisations, to ensure we gather and understand a diverse range of opinions, which helps us to design improvements to Universal Credit.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","6509","2019-10-31T17:51:08.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166656/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166656/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she plans to publish easy-to-read guidance on making a non-digital claim for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","6508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166657","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Department makes use of a range of channels to increase understanding of Universal Credit through social media and wider advertising. This includes signposting to sources of information which are written in an ‘easy-to-read’ format to help people make decisions on whether Universal Credit is appropriate for their circumstances.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We publish information in two key locations to help improve awareness of, and how to claim Universal Credit, which can be found at the following websites:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.understandinguniversalcredit.gov.uk/making-a-claim/before-you-claim/" target="_blank">https://www.understandinguniversalcredit.gov.uk/making-a-claim/before-you-claim/</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-detailed-information-for-claimants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-detailed-information-for-claimants</a></p><p> </p><p>If a person wishes to claim Universal Credit but requires assistance, they are clearly directed to either the Help to Claim service, or to the Universal Credit telephone helpline. Both can be useful to anyone who cannot use digital services.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support from helping people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time. This service is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly engage with a range of stakeholders, including welfare rights organisations, to ensure we gather and understand a diverse range of opinions, which helps us to design improvements to Universal Credit.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","6508","2019-10-31T17:51:08.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166657/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166657/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will consult (a) welfare rights advisers and (b) professionals with experience of supporting people with complex needs on drafting guidance on making a non-digital claim for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","6509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166658","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Department takes seriously the need to support vulnerable claimants, and wants the application process for Universal Credit to be as quick and easy as possible, ensuring that claimants receive money at the earliest opportunity. It is designed to be a ‘digital-first’ service, ensuring we make best use of technology to deliver a modern and effective working-age welfare system, allowing our staff to concentrate on those people who require additional support.</p><p> </p><p>Any digital claim can be treated as a non-digital claim. For instance, if a claimant’s circumstances change and contacting them digitally is no longer suitable for a short or significant period of time, agents can annotate the claim and take the same action as they would have if the claim had originally made as a non-digital claim.</p><p> </p><p>We are already committed to placing Universal Credit guidance in the House of Commons Library and last updated it on 28 March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Our Universal Credit Claimant Survey, found that 98 per cent of claimants have internet access and did claim online, and the majority of those said they found the claim process overall to be straightforward. This can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey</a></p><p> </p><p>All Jobcentre Plus offices across the country have Wi-Fi and computers available for claimants to access the internet. For those that are still unable to access or use digital services, or are not able to travel, assistance to make and maintain their claim is available via the Freephone Universal Credit helpline – which is clearly displayed on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support to help people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time, and is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Department offers comprehensive support for claimants to use our digital service, there will be occasions when people are unable to make their claim online, and so telephone applications can be accepted. In these instances, information normally available through a claimant’s online account, will be communicated in an alternative format which is best suited to an individual’s circumstances.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-31T17:59:57.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166658/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166658/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether an online universal credit claim can be converted into a non-digital claim.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","6510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166659","Department for Education","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Department has not set a deadline for the implementation of a GCSE in British Sign Language (BSL).</p><p>Implementing a GCSE in BSL requires the draft subject content to meet the rigorous requirements that apply to all GCSEs. If the content meets these criteria, at least one independent awarding organisation will need to develop a specification and have it accredited by Ofqual before a GCSE in BSL can be offered in schools. At this stage, the Department is not able to predict if or when this will happen, but we have indicated that our clear aim is to have a BSL GCSE available as soon as possible.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-11-04T17:40:27.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166659/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166659/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-28","Sign Language: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2019 to Question 872, what the timescale is for the development of the GCSE in British Sign Language; and whether his Department has set a deadline for its implementation.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","6201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166660","Department for Education","false","2019-10-31","<p><strong>‘</strong>Keeping Children Safe in Education’ is the Department’s statutory safeguarding guidance for schools and is kept under review. It sets out that all safeguarding concerns, discussions and decisions made should be recorded in writing by the school, and where appropriate, referred to children’s social care and or the police. The Department does not hold records on sexual offences in schools.</p><p>The guidance sets out how to deal with allegations that a pupil has been abused by a teacher, other member of staff or peer. It provides detailed guidance on how to manage reports of peer on peer sexual violence or sexual harassment, including those that result in a criminal conviction.</p><p>This guidance can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/keeping-children-safe-in-education--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/keeping-children-safe-in-education--2</a>, where parts 1, 4 and 5 refer to safeguarding, child on child sexual violence and sexual harassment issues.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","6363","2019-10-31T17:46:56.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166660/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166660/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-28","Schools: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what records his Department holds on sexual offences in schools.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","6362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166661","Department for Education","false","2019-10-31","<p><strong>‘</strong>Keeping Children Safe in Education’ is the Department’s statutory safeguarding guidance for schools and is kept under review. It sets out that all safeguarding concerns, discussions and decisions made should be recorded in writing by the school, and where appropriate, referred to children’s social care and or the police. The Department does not hold records on sexual offences in schools.</p><p>The guidance sets out how to deal with allegations that a pupil has been abused by a teacher, other member of staff or peer. It provides detailed guidance on how to manage reports of peer on peer sexual violence or sexual harassment, including those that result in a criminal conviction.</p><p>This guidance can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/keeping-children-safe-in-education--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/keeping-children-safe-in-education--2</a>, where parts 1, 4 and 5 refer to safeguarding, child on child sexual violence and sexual harassment issues.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","6362","2019-10-31T17:46:56.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166661/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166661/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-28","Schools: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he plans to issue guidance for schools on managing convicted perpetrators of peer-to-peer sexual offences in schools.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","6363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166662","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-31","<p>The UK continues to conduct its defence policy according to its own priorities and to assess EU capability development initiatives on that basis. For example, the UK decided not to join Permanent Structured Cooperation (PESCO). The Government has said that it may wish to participate in some EU capability development projects as part of the future partnership, on a voluntary and case-by-case basis where of clear benefit to the UK. The Withdrawal Agreement and Political Declaration provide such options to cooperate.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-10-31T15:02:44.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166662/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166662/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-10-28","EU Defence Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he has taken to ensure that UK defence priorities are not subordinate to EU capability development priorities.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","6356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166663","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Coordinated Annual Review on Defence (CARD) is a stocktake of EU Member State plans for defence spending and capability development. Non-EU countries do not participate. The UK will, however, continue to call for full coherence between CARD and NATO's Defence Planning Process to avoid unnecessary duplication and to address issues of common interest such as interoperability of military forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-10-31T15:03:22.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166663/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166663/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-10-28","EU Defence Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his policy is on the UK's defence capability being subject to the EU's Coordinated Annual Review on Defence after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","6357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166664","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-01","<p>The Secretary of State, Ministers in her Department, nor any officials in the Department for Work and Pensions, have met with such representatives.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2019-11-01T10:56:38.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166664/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166664/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether (a) she, (b) Ministers in her Department and (c) officials in her Department have met with representatives from #BackTo60, the One Voice movement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166665","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Government has made clear that EU defence initiatives should be: coherent with NATO requirements; available to NATO; and have the fullest participation of non-EU NATO Allies. Where these conditions are met, the UK can support the development of EU tools such as Permanent Structured Cooperation (PESCO).</p><p>The UK has not joined PESCO as an EU Member State, but has expressed an interest in participating in capability development projects as part of the future partnership, on a voluntary and case-by-case basis, where this is of clear benefit to the UK. PESCO-participating Member States continue to negotiate the terms on which third countries might take part in PESCO projects.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-10-31T15:01:49.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166665/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166665/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-10-28","EU Defence Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy to ensure the UK does not enter into permanent binding commitments within the EU's Permanent Structured Cooperation after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","6358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166666","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>New limits to the per draw sales, annual sales and maximum prize for society lotteries were announced on 16 July 2019. Affirmative secondary legislation is required to change the limits, and the Gambling Commission are also required to consult on changes to their Licence Conditions and Codes of Practice (LCCP). The date for laying the statutory instrument has not yet been fixed. The Gambling Commission’s consultation will also cover measures to improve transparency of society lotteries, and is expected to run for 12 weeks. The changes are expected to come into force during 2020.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","5462 ; 5463 ; 5464 ; 5465 ; 6300 ; 6304","2019-11-04T16:55:41.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166666/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166666/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries: Regulation
","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the oral statement of 16 July 2019 by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, Official Report, column 718, on Lotteries Regulation, whether the new limits on annual turnover for society lotteries will come into force by 1 January 2020.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166667","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>New limits to the per draw sales, annual sales and maximum prize for society lotteries were announced on 16 July 2019. Affirmative secondary legislation is required to change the limits, and the Gambling Commission are also required to consult on changes to their Licence Conditions and Codes of Practice (LCCP). The date for laying the statutory instrument has not yet been fixed. The Gambling Commission’s consultation will also cover measures to improve transparency of society lotteries, and is expected to run for 12 weeks. The changes are expected to come into force during 2020.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","5462 ; 5463 ; 5464 ; 5465 ; 6299 ; 6304","2019-11-04T16:55:41.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166667/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166667/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the oral statement of 16 July 2019 by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, Official Report, column 718, on Lotteries Regulation, when she plans to implement the new annual turnover limits for society lotteries.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166668","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-31","<p>The UK/EU Political Declaration states that the UK and the EU will consider UK industry participation in European Defence Fund programmes in order to facilitate interoperability and to promote joint effectiveness of our armed forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-10-31T15:04:08.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166668/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166668/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-10-28","European Defence Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy for the UK not to participate in the European Defence Fund after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","6359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166669","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>The De Minimis Assessment published alongside the Government’s consultation response sets out our assessment of the impacts on the sector and can be found here : <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/817542/Final_Society_lottery_reform_DMA_JUNE_2019.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/817542/Final_Society_lottery_reform_DMA_JUNE_2019.pdf</a>.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately",,"2019-11-04T17:05:52.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166669/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166669/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the cost of taking out an additional licence where a society lottery reaches the £10 million annual turnover limit.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166670","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Gambling Commission’s advice to DCMS on reforms to society lotteries sets out the number of lotteries within 20% of the current limits. This remains the most recent data available and shows that in 2016, 27 operators (just over 6%) were within 20% of the annual limit. The Gambling Commission’s advice has been published on their website and can be found here: <a href="http://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/PDF/consultations/Society-lottery-advice-provided-to-DCMS-002.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/PDF/consultations/Society-lottery-advice-provided-to-DCMS-002.pdf</a></p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately",,"2019-11-04T17:07:35.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166670/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166670/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the number of society lotteries that are close to reaching the £10 million annual turnover limit.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166671","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Government announced plans to raise sales and prize limits for large society lotteries in July 2019. The timeframe to introduce the new annual turnover limit is subject to the requirement for 1) the affirmative procedure of introducing secondary legislation and 2) the Gambling Commission to consult on changes to their Licence Conditions and Codes of Practice (LCCP). Taking these requirements into account we expect this change to come into force during 2020. We have not made an assessment of the impact of this timing on the sector.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","6305","2019-11-04T17:12:32.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166671/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166671/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the oral statement of 16 July 2019 by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, Official Report, column 718, on Lotteries Regulation, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of  a delay to the introduction of the new annual turnover limits beyond 1 January 2020 on (a) the hospice sector, (b) the air ambulance sector and (c) local charities.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166672","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>New limits to the per draw sales, annual sales and maximum prize for society lotteries were announced on 16 July 2019. Affirmative secondary legislation is required to change the limits, and the Gambling Commission are also required to consult on changes to their Licence Conditions and Codes of Practice (LCCP). The date for laying the statutory instrument has not yet been fixed. The Gambling Commission’s consultation will also cover measures to improve transparency of society lotteries, and is expected to run for 12 weeks. The changes are expected to come into force during 2020.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","5462 ; 5463 ; 5464 ; 5465 ; 6299 ; 6300","2019-11-04T16:55:41.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166672/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166672/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries: Lotteries: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the oral statement of 16 July 2019 by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, Official Report, column 718, on Lotteries Regulation, when she plans to bring forward secondary legislation to increase annual turnover limits.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166673","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Government announced plans to raise sales and prize limits for large society lotteries in July 2019. The timeframe to introduce the new annual turnover limit is subject to the requirement for 1) the affirmative procedure of introducing secondary legislation and 2) the Gambling Commission to consult on changes to their Licence Conditions and Codes of Practice (LCCP). Taking these requirements into account we expect this change to come into force during 2020. We have not made an assessment of the impact of this timing on the sector.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","6303","2019-11-04T17:12:32.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166673/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166673/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-28","Lotteries: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the oral statement of 16 July 2019 by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, Official Report, column 718, on Lotteries Regulation, if she will take steps to ensure that undertaking a consultation on a regulatory framework for society lotteries does not lead to a delay in implementing changes to their annual turnover limits.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166674","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-04","<p>Sentencing is a matter for the independent judiciary, which takes the full facts of each case into account. In 2018, the mean average proportion of the sentence served in prison by males released from determinate sentences (excluding extended determinate sentences) was 64%, the median proportion was 56%. For females the mean average was 49% and the median was 45%. The overwhelming majority of the releases covered by this data will be from standard determinate sentences but the way the data is recorded does not allow us readily to exclude releases from other types of determinate sentence, such as Detention and Training Orders and sentences for offenders of particular concern imposed under s.236A of the Criminal Justice Act 2003.</p>","Croydon South","Chris Philp",,"2019-11-04T17:57:21.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166674/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166674/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-28","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 22 October 2019 to Question 955 on Prison Sentences, what proportion of all standard determinate custodial sentences handed down to (a) men and (b) women were served in prison.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166675","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-05","<p>The latest data available relates to those in custody on 30 June 2018, aged 18 and over. Information is available for individuals whose relationship status had been assessed by that date on the Offender Assessment System, which accounts for 2,678 women and 62,830 men.</p><p> </p><p>i) From these totals 4,258 male prisoners were identified as having ever been the victim of domestic violence. This equates to 7% of male prisoners.</p><p> </p><p>ii) From these totals, 22% of female prisoners were identified as having ever been the perpetrator of domestic violence. This is 597 female perpetrators.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the extent of Offender Assessment System coverage exclude “layer 1” assessments, which do not include questions on domestic violence. Previous figures quoted for 2017 in the Answer of 9 October to Question 174010 included these, so percentages for 2018 are increased accordingly.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","6308","2019-11-05T12:23:45.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166675/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166675/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-28","Prisoners: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2019 to Question 1636, on Prisoners: Domestic Abuse, and with reference to the Answer of 9 October 2018 to Question 174010, on Prisoners: Domestic Abuse, if he will make an estimate using the Offender Assessment System.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166676","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-05","<p>The latest data available relates to those in custody on 30 June 2018, aged 18 and over. Information is available for individuals whose relationship status had been assessed by that date on the Offender Assessment System, which accounts for 2,678 women and 62,830 men.</p><p> </p><p>i) From these totals 4,258 male prisoners were identified as having ever been the victim of domestic violence. This equates to 7% of male prisoners.</p><p> </p><p>ii) From these totals, 22% of female prisoners were identified as having ever been the perpetrator of domestic violence. This is 597 female perpetrators.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the extent of Offender Assessment System coverage exclude “layer 1” assessments, which do not include questions on domestic violence. Previous figures quoted for 2017 in the Answer of 9 October to Question 174010 included these, so percentages for 2018 are increased accordingly.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","6307","2019-11-05T12:23:45.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166676/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166676/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-28","Prisoners: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2019 to Question 1635, on Prisoners: Domestic Abuse, and with reference to the Answer of 9 October 2018 to Question 174010, on Prisoners: Domestic Abuse, for what reasons an estimate could not be made using the Offender Assessment System.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166677","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-04","<p>We do recognise the needs of male prisoners with children, dependent or otherwise, as well as those of women. Information in this regard is vital in informing policy and practice in this area. Where male or female offenders choose to disclose such information, data is collected, although it is not corroborated. As noted in our previous answer this data does not provide detailed information of the child’s age or whether they are dependents. The data is therefore not suitable for publication.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-04T16:16:30.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166677/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166677/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-28","Prisoners: Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2019 to Question 949 on Prisoners: Parents, for what reasons his Department does not collect data to illuminate the prevalence and needs of male prisoners with children; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166678","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-11-05","<p>Health-based elements to the services provided by women’s centres may be provided through local arrangements made and funded by clinical commissioning groups but this information is not available centrally.</p>","Mid Bedfordshire","Ms Nadine Dorries",,"2019-11-05T13:00:33.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166678/answer","Biography information for Ms Nadine Dorries","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166678/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-28","Women's Centres: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding NHS England has given to Women's Centres dealing with female offenders in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166679","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>Trusts make private finance initiative (PFI) unitary payments from their annual income. The Department does not pay PFI credits to trusts. NHS England has provided data showing 2018-19 annual income for trusts with PFI schemes, which is attached.</p><p>HM Treasury publishes annual unitary charge forecast data for PFI schemes across government, including the National Health Service. The data can be found on the gov.uk website which can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2018-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2018-summary-data</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-31T17:14:13.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166679/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166679/answer","PQ6311 - Philip Davies - Spreadsheet of Turnover by Trust - PFIs.xlsx","PQ6311 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166679/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-28","Hospitals: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what each hospital's annual (a) income and (b) payment for a PFI scheme was in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166680","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>Iran's human rights record continues to be of serious concern to the UK, and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office has designated it as one of its Human Rights Priority Countries. We regularly raise the treatment of religious and ethnic minorities in Iran with the Iranian Government, and we continue to take action with the international community to press Iran to improve its poor record on all human rights issues. At the UN General Assembly in September, we brought the international community together at a UK-hosted event to shine a spotlight on Iran's human rights abuses. We will also be using Iran's forthcoming Universal Periodic Review in November, to raise concerns about the ongoing discrimination and targeting of religious minority groups, including the Christian community.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-31T16:44:04.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166680/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166680/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-28","Iran: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Iranian authorities on the treatment of Christians in that country.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","6182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166681","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>We are aware of reports about the continued harassment and mistreatment that the Christian and other minority groups face. The continued restrictions on freedoms of expression, religion and belief are deeply worrying. While some religious minorities are formally protected in the constitution, the reality is that many non-Muslims face discrimination. Despite constitutional recognition, the persecution of Christians has been continuous, systemic, and institutionalised.</p><p>We support the assessment of the UN Special Rapporteur on the Situation of Human Rights that discrimination against the Christians in Iran is sanctioned by a lack of constitutional recognition and the absence of other legal protections for adherents of this faith. We regularly call upon Iran to cease harassment of all religious minorities and to fulfil its international and domestic obligations to protect freedom of religion or belief. Work has begun to implement the recommendations from the Bishop of Truro’s Review in a way that will bring real improvements in the lives of those persecuted because of their faith or belief.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-31T16:54:38.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166681/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166681/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-28","Iran: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what monitoring his Department has undertaken of prison sentences imposed on Christian ministers and other religious figures by the Government of Iran on the basis of that people in those positions present a risk to national security.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","6183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166682","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-11-05","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Dissolution.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-11-05T16:43:23.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166682/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166682/answer","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166682/answer/previousversion/3195","Biography information for Edward Argar","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-28","Joint Replacements: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the waiting times were for (a) hip replacement and (b) knee replacement surgery in 2018-19 by NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","6403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166683","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>It is one of the guiding principles of the National Health Service that a person should have access to health services based on clinical need, irrespective of their age or disability. The NHS Constitution reaffirms this as one of the key principles underpinning all that the NHS does.</p><p>Additionally, the Equality Act 2010 and the Public Sector Equality Duty ensures that providers and commissioners of health and care services in the United Kingdom have due regard to the need to take steps to meet the needs of persons who share a relevant protected characteristic that are different from the needs of persons who do not share it. Disability and age are both protected characteristics.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-10-31T11:44:24.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166683/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166683/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-28","Disability: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to tackle the link between ageing populations and disability as part of the Government response to the UN high level meeting on universal health coverage.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","6404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166684","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Department is unable to provide data relating to (a) requested and (b) rejected alternative payment arrangements for fortnightly payment of Universal Credit as the information is not readily available, and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In response to part (c), the available information on the number of households on Universal Credit that receive More Frequent Payments or Scottish Choices More Frequent Payments is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>Statistics are based on whether a household has actually been paid a More Frequent Payment.</li><li>Data will not include households that had a More Frequent Payment set up but were not actually paid more frequently, for instance because they cancelled the More Frequent Payment before they were paid.</li></ol>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-31T17:45:27.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166684/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166684/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many alternative payment arrangements for fortnightly payment of universal credit were (a) requested, (b) rejected and (c) accepted in the most recent 12 month period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","6230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166685","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Department is unable to provide data relating to (a) requested and (b) rejected alternative payment arrangements for weekly payment of Universal Credit as the information is not readily available, and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In response to part (c), the available information on the number of households on Universal Credit that receive More Frequent Payments or Scottish Choices More Frequent Payments is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-31T17:43:54.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166685/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166685/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many alternative payment arrangements for weekly payment of universal credit were (a) requested, (b) rejected and (c) accepted in the most recent 12 month period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","6231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166686","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-31","<p>Statistics on the number of Households on Universal Credit that make use of a Managed Payment to Landlord, More Frequent Payment and Split Payments under Alternative Payment Arrangements is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Information regarding the reasons for the alternative payment arrangements is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p /><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-31T17:46:55.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166686/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166686/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many alternative payment arrangements have been arranged with universal credit claimants; and what the reasons were for those arrangements in the most recent 12 month period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","6232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166687","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-01","<p>Statistics on the number of Households on Universal Credit that make use of a Managed Payment to Landlord, More Frequent Payment and Split Payments under Alternative Payment Arrangements is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-11-01T10:44:20.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166687/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1166687/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many alternative payment arrangements have been agreed with universal credit claimants in each year since the introduction of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","6233"
